JOHANNESBURG –The Monetary Authority of Singapore has hit global banker Standard Chartered with fines amounting to $3,9-million (R47-million). The fine is for breaching money laundering rules and terrorism financing safeguards. The breaches are said to have occurred between December 2015 and January 2016, when customer account funds were transferred from the Standard Chartered Trust. READ: SAA welcomes latest bailout The bank admitted it fell short of its own standards to mitigate risks. The company says it is taking action to rectify these deficiencies. eNCA